%I A104906 #19 Mar 25 2026 00:02:52
%S A104906 1,10,831,8310
%N A104906 Numbers k such that d(k)*reversal(k)=phi(k), where d(k) is number of positive divisors of k.
%C A104906 If k is a term of this sequence and gcd(10,k)=1 then 10*k is also in the sequence because reversal(10*n)=reversal(n); d(10)=phi(10) and both functions d & phi are multiplicative.
%C A104906 a(5) > 10^12. - _Giovanni Resta_, Apr 25 2017
%C A104906 No prime terms exist, that is, for terms k > 1, d(k) >= 3. Also, there are no terms of the forms p^3 or p^6 with a prime p. - _Max Alekseyev_, Mar 24 2026
%e A104906 8310 is in the sequence because d(8310)=16; reversal(8310)=138; phi(8310)=2208 & 16*138=2108.
%t A104906 reversal[n_]:= FromDigits[Reverse[IntegerDigits[n]]]; Do[If[DivisorSigma[0, n]*reversal[n] == EulerPhi[n], Print[n]], {n, 350000000}]
%o A104906 (PARI) isok(k) = numdiv(k)*fromdigits(Vecrev(digits(k))) == eulerphi(k); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Oct 31 2025
%Y A104906 Cf. A000005, A000010, A004086.
%Y A104906 Cf. A063903, A104904, A104905, A104907.
%K A104906 nonn,base,more,changed
%O A104906 1,2
